Last weekend, three generations of the Beck family set out on their boat to harvest nearly 4,000 bushels of disease-free oysters.
Watermen agreed to wait until the oysters reached legal size, leading to a decline in oystering.
Efforts to manage oyster reserves and reduce pollution in the Chesapeake Bay are ongoing.
The introduction of Asian oysters is under scrutiny, with concerns about their impact on the ecosystem.
Despite challenges, progress has been made in clearing nutria from the marshes.
The bay cleanup effort faces delays, but stakeholders remain committed to restoring the bay's health.
